node.text:
And that’s a wrap on summer!

With the last week we crammed as much of it in as we could. We are all exhausted. Ready for bed, but not quite ready to put summer to rest. 

We have zero family photos but hundreds of new memories I’ll cherish forever from this last week. So grateful for this time and this season with them all. 

Rooting for everyone tucking in tired kids tonite, backing bags and labelling everything, pushing their anxiety into their pocket while helping them out the door and into a new chapter… we got this. We really do. Even when it’s chaos and unknowns. 🤍

node.text:
Neither of us will remember this day for the dimples on my thighs, the size of my waist or the stretch marks on my skin. 

We will remember this day for her toes in the sand. Seeing her first wave. Picking up rocks. Swimming with her sister. Experiencing a beach together. Being there. Just being there. That’s enough. 

It’s so easy to forget,
The things we catch and the things we release. 

We catch the good stuff. 
The meaningful memories. 
Like how good it felt to soak in that moment. 

We release the moments not serving us. 
Like the insecurities we carry on the day we did. 

I have to think more like this lately. Measuring and thinking on projections into the future. What WILL I remember? What do I WANT to remember? What do I want to be remembered FOR? 

Because when I think back on my own childhood and think about my mother, I carry no memories of her thighs or stretch marks or waist size. I just carry the good stuff. Her being there. Just being there. That’s enough. 

So yeah. I guess what I’m trying to say is, I know and I’ve been feeling how hard it can be in the moment, it’s hard to escape the feelings. 
But in the long haul, they don’t follow me. 

Catch and carry the good stuff. 
Release the rest.

node.text:
I thought the realization that fairy tales aren’t reality would mean a life filled with less love. Or at least, a love less great. 

Instead what it meant was that I could take the role of a great love myself. 

I could be whole, no longer waiting on a half. 

So that every decision and relationship since would build into me. Would help build me up. Help support me. And I them. 

Not a burden to be lifted up. 
But collectively, a unit to be held. 

A family. 

Just not the kind I would ever know in stories and fairy tales, anyways. 

The kind that we build. 
On our own terms. 
In our own way. 
5 whole units, choosing life together. 

This love. 
It is so big. 
It started with me. 
And them. 
Then him. 

And it really has been, just the best. 

Happy anniversary, my love. To us🤍

🎥 @yourdaybylucas
📷 @lydiaivyphotography

node.text:
It started in the 7th grade. 
Two of my “friends” starting cutting me out, and when I asked someone why they told me they said it was because I was too big. Then, a boy I liked said I was “too fat” to date. Then, another, and a few more incidents quite like this, some that I can’t even type out they remain too painful. 

Is it any surprise I started having disordered eating and feared what would happen if I gained weight?

Is it any wonder that I’ve struggled to feel valued in relationships at every size? 

I was just a girl. 
I was 12. 
It started when I was 12. 

It was engrained in me to take what I could get. Be friends with and have relationships with whoever WOULD take me. Because I was nothing to be valued. 

I’m 36 now. The little 12 year old girl now an anxiously ferocious woman. 

All along I was carrying the weight. 

And I wasn’t the problem. 
I never was. 

I was just trying to lose the wrong weight.

node.text:
I used to walk into rooms and evaluate if I were the biggest in the room. Constantly aware of my size. When I was deeply into weight loss, I began to look around the room to see if I was the smallest and if I wasn’t, there was more “work” to be done. 

Now I walk into rooms and I see people and have experiences and make memories. It’s not that I don’t notice size, I just don’t value people that way anymore. I understand that we are all meant to be different. Truly designed this way. 

I give myself the grace to change, even if that means I can’t share clothes with my friends who we were the same size last year. 
I give them the same grace to change, too. 

By policing my body by worth for how big or small I was, I was also doing that to others, even if I never would care to admit that before. Fatphobia, the low hanging fruit of a tree of society that deemed some morally better than others based on a measurement of size. 

And I picked that fruit freely for a long time.

Today, I’m being the bigger friend. 

And I hope that will be read in a way that says I choose to be the bigger person, I will always rise above hate, I will always be willing to learn from mistakes, I will always be changing & evolving. 

I will not value others by their size but by their character. I will do the same for myself. I will show up in life no matter my size. For I am a being not a body. 

So I’m bigger than some friends and smaller than others. 
In friendships with values beyond pant sizes. 
What a concept. 

Note: let us not go for “*you’re” or mocking spelling or grammar. As a parent who sees and understands the depths of learning disability I would like to not perpetuate the shaming towards this 🙏 I ALSO must acknowledge that at a size 12 I am still living with thin privilege and often the more acceptable version of a body as stores, airplanes, people are still accommodating to me. Also also, @briony what’s happening here

node.text:
I think for me my goal body has shifted. I make goals with my body. Not for my body.
Not anymore, at least. 

For instance: 
I want to swim with my babies. 
I want to hug without thinking about what that person is thinking about my waist. 
I want to wear clothes I like. 
I want to model and dance and make a fool of myself. 
I want to move in ways that makes me happy. 
I want to see the world around me! Really see it. 
I want to eat food and enjoy it, fearlessly. 

Measurements of joy. 
Instead of measurements of my body. 

I want to live a life with my body not against it. 

That is my goal. 
I’m not fully there! 
And that’s ok! 

I’m working towards it. 
And it’s different from old goals I use to have.

But every time I keep stepping into it all, the better it gets. 

🤍

Thought prompts thanks fo a recent post from  @kenziebrenna that unlocked a memory of an old pinterest board I used to have of my “goal body”. None of those images ever showed me a life they lived, just how they looked. I know that now. I’m working through it now.

node.text:
Woven within our very skin is the magic to change and adapt.

We were built for this. 
So that we do not break from this. 

Down to the very layers of who we are, 
we stretch, we grow, we become. 

So when it happens, as it does, that the guilt and doubt and shame creep in… 
as you slide your hands across the new textures and shapes and let the emotions flow as you do… 

Never forget the ✨magic✨

We were built for this. 
So that we do not break from this. 

And that some people,
just don’t believe in magic.
